title: Grateful Dead Live at Hampton Coliseum on 1992-03-05
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) >KORG AudioGate 4 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/24
description:
Set 1

Help On The Way-> Slipknot!-> Franklin's Tower, The Same Thing, Jack A Roe, Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues, Let It Grow

Set 2

Eyes Of The World-> Way To Go Home, Estimated Prophet-> He's Gone-> Drums-> Jam-> The Wheel-> I Need A Miracle-> So Many Roads-> Good Lovin', E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text:
Hindsight At the time, I found this show very disappointing. Help> Slip> Frank's was missing the "umph" I desired that hat trick to deliver. Same Thing was cool, and the first set waddled along. My primary problem was having been spoiled with the Warlocks 10/9/89 show, a tough bit to outshine. Jerry's show the previous November had also set the bar high.

Naturally, the Eyes opener to the second set ignited 3/29/90-ish hopes, but one cannot turn back the clock. Long Way was a bit of a shock to the system. It felt as though Vince was sneering at both his critics and fans. That was an unusual feeling at a Dead show, to be honest. Ouch. From Estimated on, the show improves. Being from Maine, the Drums was special with the featured loons. The Space-> Wheel is rather tasty, and my first So Many Roads sent shivers down me spine.

Hindsight suggests that I should have been more appreciative at the time. Expectations can be that way: we miss the special treats by wanting the gargantuan explosions of a grande finale. Looking back, I can forgive myself. It was tough to top the 87 through 91 run. 

Hampton still rules, though, no matter what.

As always, Miller's mastering slays.
